European inflation slipped on food
The accelerating inflation in the euro area is mainly due to the rapid increase in food prices.
The 13 euro area countries recorded higher than expected price increases in November, with annual inflation of 3.1% after 2.6% in October, the EU's statistical office in Luxembourg reported.
The official forecast was only 3 percent, Bloomberg reported.
Unlike the US, UK and Canadian central banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) has not cut the base rate, saying that the reduction would lead to a spiral of inflation, along with rising commodity prices and easing unemployment.
The ECB wants to keep the inflation rate below 2 percent, but close to that.
One analyst says that the ECB is in the twenty-second trap: "we need to talk down" inflation so that we don't have to act on it later.
In Germany, November inflation was a 12-year record at 3.3%, while in Spain it rose from 3.6% to 4.1.
Eurozone inflation was boosted by soaring food and energy prices.
Wheat futures rose 88 percent, and soybean prices reached their highest level since 1973.
The cost of food and dairy products was also substantially higher in 2007.
The world market price of crude oil has risen 52 percent this year, and last month it was almost $100 a barrel of black gold.
According to the ECB, inflation will jump from 2.1% this year to 2.5% in 2008 and fall to 1.9% in 2009.
Analysts estimate that the 12-month inflation rate will remain around 3% over the next 3-4 months, but the annual average rate will be 2.1%.
At the same time, the ECB is expected to cut interest rates twice during 2008.
Gallup sees a government crisis
After a long stagnation, Fidesz's support had grown significantly by early December, so it now has the largest camp since 2002, while Gallup had never before measured such low, 13 percent socialist support.
The difference in the votes of the committed parties, due to the greater determination of the opposition voters, would represent more than two-thirds (71%) support, compared with one-fifth (20%) support for the SME.
The MDF and the SZDSZ are below the parliamentary threshold according to the survey: their support within the total population is two percent.
The number of people who vote for certain parties is one percent higher than the number who support either side.
The economic mood is likely to deteriorate further to the previous low - never before so high, with 41 percent of those who rated the country's economic situation as particularly bad, while another 46 percent said it was quite bad.
After the spring and summer prospects were more optimistic, families are now more pessimistic about the change in their own financial situation.
For the next year, more than half the population expects further deterioration and only a tenth improvement.
In December, more than in any previous Gallup poll, 71 percent of those polled thought the prime minister was doing a bad job than a good job.
In Gyurcsány Ferenc, 13 percent of the respondents trust or very trust him, while in Viktor Orbán, 38 percent of the supporters are.
