In many places, disinfectants are being cut back
This year, more than a thousand infections have been reported in hospitals, mainly due to improper use of antibiotics.
The hygienic conditions in hospitals, the overcrowding of beds, and the overload of staff are not conducive to stopping infections, says the chief medical officer of the National Epidemiology Center.
In many places, they're saving on disinfectants.
Recently, an MRSA infection was diagnosed in the trauma department of John's Hospital.
A man who was in a serious accident was shown to have bacteria resistant to antibiotics.
The patient has been isolated.
A similar infection occurred here earlier this year.
A serious car accident victim was released from the hospital, but soon afterward he had to return with MRSA infection and an important surgery had not been performed since because of the bacteria in his body.
As of December 10, this year, 1,094 hospital infections caused by multi-drug resistant pathogens were reported to the National Nosocomial Surveillance System, said Dr. Karolina Böröcz, chief medical officer of the National Epidemiology Center.
That means that this many infections caused by the M.R.B.s must have been registered in hospitals, the rest is unknown.
Approximately two thirds (683) of the infections were caused by MRSA, or methicillin-oxacillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus.
Staphylococcus aureus (SA) is carried by one third of the human population through the nose without causing disease.
Infections caused by SA (e. g. strep throat, tonsillitis, skin infections, wound infections) respond well to antibiotics and are well curable.
However, if antibiotics are used in excess or inadequately, a bacterium that responds well to antibiotics will develop into a highly antibiotic-resistant bacterium that spreads rapidly in inadequate hospital conditions.
In particular, temporary or permanent immune system dysfunction can cause serious hospital infections such as wound infections or blood poisoning - sepsis - in patients with weakened bodies, the elderly or those with low body weight.
According to the medical director of János Hospital, there is nothing unusual about MRSA infection, such infections are part of the daily practice of hospitals.
Infection should not be confused with plague, MRSA is only present, Rabbit Tibor said, where the presence of the pathogen is not tested.
Resistant to antibiotics
"We isolate such patients, the nursing staff see the patient in rubber gloves and a mask, and there are adequate antibiotics to treat them", said Tibor Nyulasi.
Patients admitted to hospital are tested for MRSA, but infection cannot always be avoided.
It's not fashionable to sample
The vast majority of hospital infections caused by MRSA are preventable, but the current conditions and conditions in hospitals are not conducive to preventing the development and spread of multi-drug resistant pathogens, says Böröcz Karolina.
Since this infection typically occurs in hospitals, nursing homes, hospitals should monitor incoming patients and isolate MRSA-carrying patients immediately.
However, microbiological sampling is not in vogue in Hungarian hospitals.
The fact that the National Health Insurance Fund does not finance these studies also plays a role.
Most cases are detected when the patient has a detectable MRSA infection, said the chief medical officer of the epidemiological center.
The European Union has strict recommendations for the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine and national guidelines for the treatment of certain infections and pathologies.
The aim is to make antibiotic therapy targeted, i.e. microbiological tests should be carried out to prevent drug resistance, but hospitals do not always follow this.
Microbiological sampling is even rarer in the commuter and primary care settings, said Karolina Böröcz.
They save on disinfectants
Scientific evidence shows that MRSA is most commonly transmitted from one patient to another through healthcare personnel.
So, there is a huge role for hand washing, gloves, masks, but there are also significant gaps in hospitals.
MRSA is transmitted by contact and drip infection, but isolation of an infected patient is not always possible in a home hospital setting.
In fact, hospital rooms are often crowded, often with beds very close together, even though, epidemiologically, patients should be at least five feet apart.
Sadly, Karolina Böröcz noted, hospitals in poor economic conditions are also sparing on disinfectants, with fewer nurses and more patients, making infections even more likely.
According to Karolina Böröcz, where appropriate precautions are taken, fewer such infections can be detected or the spread of the pathogen can be stopped.
Government programme against MRSA
MRSA infection is a huge cost to health care companies, so they're fighting it everywhere.
In England, for example, the government has included in its programme the prevention and reduction of MRSA.
The programme appears to be successful, with the data reported showing a declining trend in MRSA infections in England.
Prevention of the development of multi-drug resistant pathogens (including MRSA) and of hospital-acquired infections caused by such pathogens is one of the priorities of the European Centre for Disease Prevention (ECDC).
