Bulgaria is the EU's real estate paradise
The development of the Bulgarian real estate market is astonishing - the whole of Europe is focused on the Balkan country, which was mentioned only a little earlier.
What, where and who are buying in the EU's still cheapest but fastest-growing market?
Analysis of the Bulgarian division of Re/Max.
The most sought-after destination for real estate in Eastern Europe is undoubtedly Bulgaria, with its cheap ski apartments and beach houses.
The hills are the most fashionable in Banszko, Borovec, Pamprovo and Vitosa, and along the coast are Albena, the "Golden Coast", the "Sunshine Coast", ancient Sozopol and Nesebar, but more and more people are looking for real estate in the Kavarna and Balchik areas.
Re/Max Bulgaria's analysts believe that sooner or later the central part of the country will also attract investors - Veliko Tarnovo, Gabrovo, Elena, Triavna - and that more and more people will also shop in the extremely cheap Rusz area.
The capital, Sofia, also offers attractive opportunities, with commercial and office spaces offering the highest returns.
Bulgaria is well on its way to becoming one of the most attractive European golf destinations, making it a prime destination in the other two seasons as well as in the summer and winter seasons.
Forward-looking investors are therefore already buying in large quantities, for example in the Banszko area.
Analysts say that property buyers in Bulgaria are also looking to change their lives and lifestyles.
Most of the buyers are English, but they come from France, Belgium, Spain and increasingly from Romania.
Maltese and Cypriot investors are also present, and the Black Sea and ski resorts traditionally have a large number of Russian buyers.
Foreign buyers can be classified into three groups, says Georgij Jankov, Regional Director of Re/Max Bulgaria.
The newcomers either buy renovated properties for between EUR 50 and EUR 100 000, or old houses that have been demolished for EUR 5 to EUR 15 000, and then renovate them.
They need good accessibility and communication facilities, and they are keen to be close to a big city, shops and, in general, the local doctor.
The second category is holidaymakers (Bulgaria was in the top 10 German holiday destinations in December).
The third group is made up of business investors who buy in the hope of increasing their value in the medium or long term.
The price of capital property is continuing to rise as demand grows.
Although Bulgaria has the lowest property prices in the European Union, it has been growing at a rate of 21 percent a year for the past five years.
The increase in real estate prices is essentially outpacing the increase in salaries.
Fodor and the Hungarian six percent
According to Minister of Environment and Water Affairs Fodor Gábor, the expert meetings will end on Tuesday, and the international climate regime negotiations after 2012 will continue with the ministerial meeting after the official opening on Wednesday.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries around the world are discussing the Bali Roadmap, which provides for efforts following the emission reduction period set by the Kyoto Protocol for 2012.
This is a hotly debated issue between developing and developed countries.
The United States has also indicated that it does not wish to negotiate exact figures at this time, although it is inclined to agree to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 25-40% by 2020 compared to 1990 levels.
Another big question at the conference is whether the developed countries will, in addition to reducing emissions, also provide financial and technological assistance to countries that need it.
The Commission has also agreed to provide aid to developing countries.
The grant fund, which is provided for in the Kyoto Protocol, will be managed by a 16-member board of directors, expected to be within the UN Global Environment Facility (GEF), see Market and Profit.
6 percent of Hungary
Minister for Environment and Water Affairs Fodor Gábor, on behalf of Hungary, supports the EU's efforts to maintain its flagship role in global climate action and to help create a new international agreement by 2009.
The Minister explained that the EU is committed to a 20% reduction in greenhouse gas emissions by 2020 compared to 1990 levels, irrespective of the success of the 'post-2012 agreement', and is ready to commit to a reduction of up to 30% if other large developed regions of the world and developing countries are also willing to make commitments commensurate with their responsibilities and capabilities.
Fodor Gábor pointed out that in 1997 the Kyoto Protocol had set a target of a reduction of 5,2% for all countries, of which the EU, which was then 15 Member States, had committed minus 8%.
Hungary's commitment is to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 6 percent compared to the period 1985-87, which Hungary will meet. - reminds the press release of the Ministry of Environment.
The stakes are high in Bali, where the long-term international climate agreement must be capped within two years, or else its entry into force would be delayed until after 2012, in which case the Kyoto Protocol reduction commitments would not be immediately followed by a new international emission reduction system, the need for which was highlighted by the IPCC, the UN's Nobel Peace Prize-winning international scientific body on climate change, in its latest report.
This would delay the reduction of emissions and make an increase in the average temperature of the earth of over 2 degrees Celsius inevitable, with consequences that scientists say are extremely serious and irreversible.
YouTube is recruiting the British Army
Video footage of operations in Iraq and Afghanistan is being shared on video by British Army units to promote themselves.
The British Air Force (RAF) was the first to get on YouTube: Special Forces in Afghanistan have been uploading videos of their operations against the Taliban since March 2006, the BBC reported.
These miniature images, taken with a helmeted camera, are checked at the Air Force operations headquarters in Kandahar and then sent to London, where the locals upload them to the Internet.
The political message is inevitable
139 videos of the Air Force soldiers have been uploaded to the Internet in this form, and their "channel" has been viewed by over 75,000 people.
The British Ministry of Defence registered as Defenceheadquarters in the spring of 2007 and publishes videos of both the Iraq and Afghanistan operations, while the British Commonwealth Office and the International Peace Keeping Forces in Iraq (MNFI) also have their own YouTube channels.
Operation in Afghanistan
The Air Force originally intended the videos to be for recruitment purposes, and the Department of Defense says it's also good for educating the public about the true purpose of the military's foreign presence.
Propaganda in this form costs little compared with traditional television advertising, defense expert Gordon Mackenzie told the BBC, but it inevitably carries a political message, as it provides a specific form of justification for military action by the government.
The Americans were making a game
The army also has a problem with carefully edited, censored footage and amateur videos that are shared, such as those showing soldiers dying: in the slightly hypocritical "official" propaganda films, the officers talk about casualties at the most, but do not show the bloody side of the battle.
There are, by the way, a number of videos of the battlefields in Iraq and Afghanistan that have been leaked online, and they're taken in the context of intense combat, but the British military has only recently been able to access them.
The Americans are recruiting a little differently with the free-to-download shooter game America's Army, in which the player can go directly into the shoes of soldiers in a more or less lifelike simulation.
