Political Capital: Hungarian Guard has raised the risk of the country
The activities of the Hungarian Guard, which was founded in August this year with the support of the Jobbik Movement for Hungary, have also raised the political risk of Hungary and the region in several respects, according to the Risk Analysing Division of Political Capital.
The company's "risk warning" stated that the greatest political risk in connection with the activities of the Hungarian Guard is that "the ethnic tension between the Roma and non-Gypsy population in Hungary, which already exists, could lead to violent ethnic clashes in the short term".
The main reason for this is that the political strategy of the Hungarian Guard is probably aimed at provoking such an act - the research institute added.
As they wrote, this can be traced back to one of the most important failures of Hungarian politicians: "public debate on the Roma issue was allowed by public actors to representatives of radical and extremist political groups who could build a political strategy against the Gypsy-Hungarian opposition".
This deepens the problem, makes normal dialogue impossible, strengthens extremists, and increases the likelihood of violent conflict, they believe.
In addition, the research institute said that the activities of the Hungarian Guard, due to the large domestic and international media attention, "significantly eroded the image of Hungary abroad, especially in terms of the country's stability and democratic development".
It is recalled that as part of the reorganization of the radical and far-right groups in Hungary, which has gained increasing publicity and momentum since the autumn of 2006, several organizations calling themselves "national self-defense" associations have been formed in Hungary since the summer of 2007.
"The common feature of these groups is that they define themselves as a civilian organization, while openly promoting the preparation of their members - even armed - for defensive (catastrophe, homeland defense, law enforcement) tasks, and also citing the incompetence of the police, the army, i.e. the state", they added.
They noted that this was done in accordance with the method of putting different political aspirations into civilian clothing, based on the political and non-partisan nature of society.
The emphasis on civility and the form of association is therefore not only a means of avoiding legal obstacles to the registration of such associations, but also a political strategy.
The analysis shows that the activities of the Hungarian Guard are a risk-increasing factor also in terms of neighbourly relations.
"In recent months, several neighboring states have also referred to the Hungarian Guard as a potential source of danger, and some ultra-nationalist political actors in neighboring countries want to justify their own anti-Hungarian policy by referring to the creation of the Hungarian Guard.
All this affects the political stability of the region", they added.
According to the research institute, the formation of the Hungarian Guard is not a unique phenomenon in Eastern-Central Europe, so political risks have increased for the whole region.
As reported, the Hungarian Guard operates similarly to the Bulgarian National Guard, which was announced in August 2007 by the far-right Bulgarian National Union (BNU).
The background to the formation of the Bulgarian Guard is the mass Roma riots that broke out in a district of Sofia (Kraszna Poljana).
The BNU took advantage of this and decided to establish the Guards, saying that the purpose of the organization was "national self-defense".
They say that "gypsy terror" has been going on in Bulgaria for the past 17 years, but the state has remained passive and indifferent, recalls Political Capital.
They added that the initiative had caused a heated debate in the Bulgarian public.
As reported, the increased risk of ethnic clashes is indicated by the fact that some Romani organizations in Bulgaria have announced that they will create their own guards as a resistance.
Since the Hungarian Guard's previous operations have similarities to those of the Bulgarian National Guard, it cannot be ruled out that the Roma in Hungary will respond to the threat in a similar way, by organizing their own self-defense - according to the risk warning of Political Capital.
Juhász Attila, research director at Political Capital, told the telegraph office that risk analysis is one of the research institute's activities.
As he said, they publish their risk analysis every year, and if they find something that could affect the change in risk, they inform the public, as in this case by issuing a risk warning.
Not everywhere is a red letter
In Hungary, the law accurately marks the days in red, and around the holidays it has become common practice to rearrange the working day, which will be less next year.
The holiday is not uniform in the EU and the US.
The Hungarian legal system distinguishes between national and state holidays and public holidays.
The holidays are usually associated with religious holidays and historical events.
We also celebrate New Year's Day, the last day of the previous year and the first day of the new year, both days of rest - the latter just so that the New Year's celebrants can relax.
