Depressing Memories
After more than 60 years of secrecy, the Bad Arolsen archive has been made public, documenting the fate of the 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime.
The 47 million archival documents, which occupy 27 kilometres of shelves in Bad Arolsen in the state of Hesse, have so far been searchable only for 'humanitarian' purposes, i.e. they have provided unique and anonymous access to the victims or their descendants.
In May 2006, 11 countries, including Germany, France, Israel, and the United States, agreed to open the archive to researchers and historians.
After all the states ratified the convention, the archives were opened yesterday.
Confidential information
The opening of the Bad Arolsen library will allow historians to conduct research "on the transfer of prisoners, the inhabitants of the camps, and the health of forced laborers", explains Reto Meistern, director of the archive run by the International Committee of the Red Cross.
Until now, several states, including Germany, have opposed the release of the documents, as they contain names and therefore confidential information.
For example, some deported victims may have a presumed homosexuality or mental disability.
After the war, the Gestapo began collecting concentration camp records and arrest warrants for practical reasons, to search for civilians who had been deported or sentenced to forced labor and to provide evidence of their internment, which could be used to obtain compensation.
More than 300 permanent staff are already working in Bad Arolsen to handle tens of thousands of individual requests.
However, some in the academic community do not consider the opening of the Bad Arolsen archive to be of great significance.
"These documents are basically nothing new", said Professor Wolfgang Benz, director of the Center for Research on Anti-Semitism at the Technical University of Berlin, in 2006.
