Congress approves the adoption of MiFID, which goes into effect on November 1st.
In parallel with the parliamentary process, which ended today with a congressional vote approving the Senate amendments, the government has initiated a social dialogue on the regulations underlying the law so that both can come into force before the end of the year.
The representatives of the various groups unanimously highlighted the efforts made by the Members and Senators in negotiations and agreements to establish the most favourable rules for the protection of investors and to regulate the activities of companies in detail in order to ensure the efficient functioning of the market.
Mifid, which amends the Securities Markets Act, allows for the modernisation of financial markets, while strengthening investor protection, extending the supervisory powers of the Spanish National Securities Market Commission (CNMV) and promoting cooperation between the various supervisors in the European Union.
The new Directive allows for the provision of financial advice to specialist firms, but also to natural or legal persons, and creates a new form of financial service provider (ESIS) in addition to securities companies, securities agencies and portfolio management companies, namely financial advisory firms (AFI).
In addition, the Act increases the number of systems capable of executing operations involving funds, thus adding to the regulated secondary markets multilateral trading platforms and order-filling internalisations which compete with existing stock exchange operators.
The Act also requires investment firms to provide market information on the aspects that determine their business profile, risk-taking and risk management methods, and to facilitate the control of the CNMV, they must keep records of all transactions carried out.
The House Committee on Economic Affairs has made a number of changes, most notably treating securitised debt as a "complex" asset because of the high risk to the investor, which is a fact of the U.S. subprime mortgage crisis.
On the other hand, the transposition of the directive has also been used to legally define the scope of activities of those with economic and business qualifications, 30 years after the Royal Decree of 1977 which defined the professional functions exclusively for economists came into force.
The Senate also proposed the creation of new players in the financial sector, such as an intermediary agent who works for another account, does not need the authorisation of the CNMV and can simultaneously market products or acquire clients for several investment companies.
