More fears over the Russian-Ukrainian gas dispute
The gas dispute between Ukraine and Russia has been renewed, which may also affect Russian fuel to be shipped to Western Europe.
Most Russian gas exported to the European Union (EU) is transported through Ukraine and disputes between the two nations have always attracted much attention.
Kiev has stated that if Moscow raises the price of gas to be paid by the Ukrainians, they will also hit Russia with higher transit costs.
A dispute between the two countries last year led to a drop in supplies to EU countries.
The latest dispute between Kiev and Moscow concerns an attempt by the Ukrainian government and Russia's state-owned gas monopoly Gazprom to agree on the amount of gas Ukraine is to pay to Russia in 2008.
Gazprom has stated that it will have to implement a 50% increase in gas produced from neighbouring Turkmenistan compared to the 2008 price agreement with Ukraine.
According to analysts, this could mean a 40% increase in the price of Gazprom's deliveries to Ukraine.
"It is important to argue in the negotiations in accordance with one of the most important transit states for natural gas", Ukrainian Economy Minister Anatoly Kinah told Reuters news agency.
'The changes in gas prices should be linked to the ongoing debate on the level of costs of transit through Ukraine (and into Western Europe).'
As a result of the last major gas dispute between Moscow and Kiev, Gazprom closed the gas pipeline to Ukraine in January 2006.
This resulted in a domino-like decrease in exports to Western Europe, which also greatly depressed prices.
