The NHS 'must check foreign workers'
Scottish NHS committees need to improve their control of criminal records for workers arriving from outside Europe, a watchdog said.
The proposal was made by the Auditor-General, Robert Black, following a report in Scotland linking a foreign doctor to the attack on Glasgow airport in June.
Black also expressed concern that NHS Scotland did not have accurate figures on the number of overseas employees.
However, in its report, it also pointed out key controls that were properly carried out through a sample of five health authorities.
Following the attack on Glasgow Airport, the Auditor-General checked the list of employees recruited from outside the European Economic Area.
Bilal Abdullah, 28, an Iraqi-born doctor at the Royal Alexandra Hospital in Paisley, was arrested at the airport after a jeep crashed into the main terminal of the building.
Abdullah was one of three doctors interviewed by video link at the Old Bailey in October on charges of attempted car bombings in the UK.
NHS committees should check the qualifications and work experience of their overseas staff and their availability of the necessary authorisations to work in the UK before they start their employment.
Although the Scottish Health Boards use Disclosure Scotland to verify criminal records, the Agency is not authorised to obtain information of this kind from outside the UK.
The Auditor-General's report proposed, inter alia, that the committees should introduce a Criminal Records Office guide, which would facilitate the employer's control processes with various overseas countries.
"Although evidence of such checks has been found in staff records, they are not carried out on a regular basis", the report states.
Black said that although the NHS in Scotland is performing its own pre-employment screening process at a high level, he added: 'Our report highlights areas where the system can be improved to ensure that we have up-to-date information on the number of staff coming from overseas in the NHS.'
Dr Peter Terry, President of BMA Scotland, said it was "extremely unrealistic" that pre-employment checks could be used to identify potential NHS staff who might commit terrorist acts in the future.
"The report shows that the pre-employment checks currently in place are working well in NHS Scotland and the value of the proposals is not yet transparent", he added.
The Scottish Health Authority estimates that their current overseas staff, mostly doctors and nurses, is 1,161.
However, the Auditor-General pointed out that the figures are likely to be higher, partly because committees have problems identifying employees on indefinite leave.
The investigation also showed that the control procedures in place in the NHS authorities in Ayrshire and Arran, Grampian, Greater Glasgow and Clyde, Lanarkshire and Lothian are highly coordinated.
These procedures extended to the checking of passports, work permits and documents certifying professional qualifications.
The Scottish Government is currently examining the Guidelines and Guidelines for pre-employment checks for NHS staff from overseas.
Health Secretary Nicola Sturgeon said: 'I am very pleased that this task has been achieved following the attack on Glasgow Airport.
He added that the Scottish Government, in cooperation with the Health Committees, would take into account the suggestions contained in the report and ensure that the updated guidance on pre-employment checks for the entire staff pool, including those from overseas, reflected best practice.
