Venus' climate may provide a glimpse into the future of Earth
Scientists yesterday concluded that Venus once provided a pleasant environment for life.
Data from a European orbiting spacecraft suggest that this planet may be a much more likely windy twin of Earth than previously thought.
Venus is the closest planetary neighbor to Earth.
The two planets are almost the same size and orbit similarly, although Venus is slightly closer to the sun.
Scientists now know that billions of years ago, Venus could have had conditions very similar to Earth's and even habitable conditions.
But the explosive greenhouse effect, atmospheric erosion by solar radiation, and the planet's slower rotation have put Venus on a different course of evolution.
Now the water has evaporated from the planet, the surface temperature is hot enough to melt lead, and hurricane-force winds and lightning storms are destroying it.
The findings of the European Space Agency's Venus Express spacecraft, based on a year's study of the planet, paint a sobering picture of how similar catastrophic climate changes could occur on Earth.
Fred Taylor, a professor in the Department of Physics at Oxford University and one of the leaders of the Venus Express mission, said: "It is beginning to be understood why the climate of Venus is so different from that of Earth, even though the two planets are very similar in structure.
"Our new data have made it possible to develop a scenario of the formation of Venus billions of years ago, when it may have had habitable conditions similar to Earth.
