Another chasm lies ahead of Gordon Brown; the way out remains unchanged
Compared to the British political scandals, this one doesn't seem too spicy.
No one has sold his honor, no politician has been exposed to his Paris hotel bills, no one has committed an extra-marital scandal.
But the discovery that a wealthy businessman had contributed more than £650,000 (US$1.3 million) to Britain's governing Labour Party under the name of others over four years, and that the party had not reported it, was one of the things that would have kept the circumcised Gordon Brown in line.
Two months ago, when the Prime Minister got away with his election and when he recklessly questioned the intelligence of the British people by saying that polls had no bearing on the outcome of the election, people were still hoping that Brown would provide a strong and effective government.
But instead, as Vince Cable, the Liberal Democrat's deputy leader, who has been making increasingly witty remarks, has noted, the once-feared Brown has transformed from Stalin to Mr. Bean.
The rescue of the struggling Northern Rock bank has put regulatory weaknesses and shortcomings in judgment at a crossroads.
The patient proposals to change the tax code have encouraged business interest groups to unite against the government.
The loss of personal data of 25 million people by the tax authorities revealed an unimaginable level of maladministration.
In the House of Lords, three retired generals have stirred up a row over cuts to the military budget, claiming that the position of Minister of Defence is a part-time job.
And now here are the secret donations of David Abrahams, Peter Watt, the Labour Party's general secretary (formerly administrative leader) has resigned.
These accidents don't mean Brown can't turn back on the way to the exit.
At the same time, governments can reach a point where control becomes impossible.
People do not like politicians or trust them, but when a new group comes to power, they usually suspend their distrust.
But once it becomes clear that the prime minister is unlikely to be fit to lead the way, and perhaps not to stay in office for long, the suspended mistrust ends: the civil service begins to leak, cabinet ministers begin to leak, the press looks for bad news; and the government becomes defensive and unable to concentrate.
In a sense, Brown is particularly difficult because, unlike other political leaders, he is not considered "fresh blood".
As much as he'd like to deny his connection to Tony Blair, he was his right-hand man.
For example, the problems with Northern Rock and the tax records are related to decisions made during Brown's tenure as Treasury Secretary.
And while he was not directly involved in Blair-like actions, such as his protracted investigation into the relationship between the "nobility for money" case and political party funding, voters can rightly assume otherwise.
Although Brown's situation is uncomfortable, it's not as embarrassing as it seems.
The shooting is not as scary as the Tories make it out to be.
As with Mr. Bean, no one died, no one was directly involved.
And the compensation, however painful, could be the creation of the direction that Stalin in Brown has always promised: reliable, solid and somewhat tough government.
A good example is the political funding scandal.
The shy Abrahams, who likened his donations to charity, said he did not want his donation to be made public.
Perhaps, but it was not his decision to make.
The law banning the anonymity of major political supporters is clear and clearly justified: the public has a right to know who is knocking at the door of the country's leaders.
Watt, who said he knew about Abrahams's move but was unaware of its illegal nature, will likely be sweated during the hearings, as will Jon Medleson, the Labour Party's foundation chairman, who learned of the disruptive donations in October.
Brown, on the other hand, is not in the loop: there is no indication that he knew about these coils, not even that the huge sums were paid after Brown took office in June.
