Fastow, responsible for the numerous fraud schemes that bankrupted Enron, also controlled the Enron subsidiary in which Greenwich NatWest invested.
At the beginning of 2002, the bank was not aware of any existing shareholding in the subsidiary, but the three British men were well aware of the very high level of interest.
A company run by Kopper bought the bank's $1 million stake in the subsidiary.
The bankers paid Kopper $250,000 to get a stake in this company.
The indictment alleges that Fastow falsely informed Enron that the energy company was buying a $20 million stake in a subsidiary of Greenwich NatWest.
