Venus is the Earth's evil twin.
Despite its rugged atmosphere, Venus is more like Earth than previously thought: In its orbit, the European spacecraft Venus Express detected lightning and at its poles, winds like those that occur on Earth in winter.
For nearly three decades, scientists have assumed that Venus is lightning.
The European spacecraft Venus Express has provided evidence - it detected electromagnetic waves at the edge of the atmosphere: "Venus's lightning strikes from cloud to cloud on wheels 35 miles [56 km] high", reports Christopher Russell of the University of California, Los Angeles, in the journal Nature.
The famous "soup theory" suggests that lightning caused life on earth: Storms triggered reactions in the ocean that led to the formation of amino acids, the building blocks of life.
Not so with Venus: "If life ever existed there, it must have been in very early times", explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution of Washington.
At present, there is little living on the surface of Venus: The atmosphere is 100 times denser than on Earth, and temperatures can reach 500 degrees Celsius.
"Venus may be the infernal twin of Earth, but it is a twin", Russell pointed out.
The central question of the ESA mission is why Venus, so similar in mass and size to Earth, is on a completely different evolutionary path.
The launch of the Venus Express in November 2005 was a milestone in the search for Venus, for no probe has been on the road since the early 1990's specifically to explore this planet.
The latest research, already presented in several Nature articles, is more than just proof that Venus is unique in the solar system, according to researchers.
"They also suggest that the similarity of the neighboring planet to Earth is greater than originally assumed", Esa reported.
In addition to the already known Arctic gyrosphere, researchers have discovered an even faster-moving cloud cloud at the South Pole.
The phenomenon is reminiscent of the air currents of the Earth's winter hemisphere, says a research team led by Giuseppe Piccioni of the Italian Institute of Astrophysics and Space and Cosmic Physics.
The second innermost planet in the solar system is nearly the same mass as Earth, and at a diameter of some 12,000 miles [12,100 km], it is almost the same size as Earth.
Also called the Evening Star, it orbits the sun in just 225 days.
However, it orbits its own body much more slowly: a Venus day lasts 243 Earth days.
Although Venus' surface temperature, at 92 bar, is barely Earthlike, scientists assume that both planets formed under very similar conditions.
Both had water accumulated, which remained as an ocean on Earth, while on Venus it left for the universe.
