These aren't Warhol's boxes.
If you think of Sweden and your village, you're thinking of Ikea, not Andy Warhol.
Or is it?
At present, Swedish-made faucets cast a dark shadow on Warhol's list of works.
Most of the 94 'Stockholm type' Brillo Boxes listed here are counterfeits.
After the Swedish newspaper Expressen questioned the authenticity of Andy Warhol's 1968 Brillo Boxes a few months ago, an internal investigation by the Moderna Museet in Stockholm has now yielded a sobering result: six copies of the "Brillo Box" donated to Moderna Museet in 1995 by Pontus Hultén, a former museum director - and, most likely, many of the hundreds of other "Stockholm-style" Brillo Boxes on the international art market.
The prehistory is a long and complicated chain of artistic and curatorial displays.
Warhol created the first "Brillo Boxes" in New York City in 1964, painted boxes based on the red-blue-white design of the "Brillo" soap powder carton.
At a 1968 exhibition of his work at the Moderna Museet, hundreds of Brillo boxes made of cardboard were displayed with Warhol's permission: These were not from Warhol (for cost-saving reasons) but shipped directly from the Brillo carton factory.
They were not works of art, but their templates, simple exhibits.
However, in 1968 Warhol authorized the manufacture of some Brillo-falladium in Sweden, but these were not exhibited at the Moderna Museet.
Witnesses of the time now speak of fifteen boxes in a row which, certified at the time as Original-Andy-Warhol-Brillo-Box under the designation 'Stockholm type', have rightfully entered the history of art and auction.
Some of them sold for over $100,000.
The problem, however, is that Pontus Hultén, the legendary museum director, later falsely claimed that in 1968 a hundred wheelbarrows were made and exhibited in Sweden, which he then left to Warhol.
In fact, Hultén's box 105 was only made in 1990 in Malmö for an exhibition in St. Petersburg.
By this time, Warhol had been dead for three years.
In addition to the six Brillo Boxes owned by the museum, Lars Byström, chief curator of the Moderna Museet, examined three private boxes in Sweden, two of which were made in Stockholm in 1968: The pressed sheets were first grounded and polished, then brushed with white oil paint.
However, the structure of the 1990 copies indicates that the paint was applied directly to the rolling plate with a paint roller without a base - and it is not oil paint, but acrylic paint.
"These boxes were not authenticated by the artist and should be removed from the official list of Andy Warhol Brillo Boxes", says Lars Nittve, director of Moderna Museet: "Unless the Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board in New York decides otherwise, Moderna Museet will classify the six boxes in its collection as copies/exhibits".
The Authentication Board, of course, announced back in June that it was investigating "serious allegations" about soap cans.
But since then, they have been shrouded in implacable silence.
